{"title_page": "Alex Harvey (country musician)", "text_new": "{{About|the American singer/songwriter from Tennessee|the Scottish musician|The Alex Harvey Band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Alex Harvey\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter, author, actor, radio host\n| birth_name       = Thomas Alexander Harvey\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1941|3|10}}\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2020|4|4|1941|3|10}}\n| genre            = [[Americana (music)|Americana]]\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[United Artists]], [[Buddah Records|Buddah]], [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]]\n| birth_place      = [[Haywood County, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| website          = http://deltadawn.org\n}}\n'''Thomas Alexander Harvey''' (March 10, 1941<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/statesman/obituary.aspx?n=thomas-harvey&pid=195919421&fhid=12001 Thomas Harvey 1941-2020]</ref> \u2013 April 4, 2020) was an American singer, songwriter, author, actor, and radio host.\n\n== History ==\nAlex Harvey was born in rural western Tennessee near [[Brownsville, Tennessee|Brownsville]]. In 1964, Harvey graduated from [[Murray State University]] in Kentucky with a Master's Degree in Music and Education, and he also studied acting in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1974|title=Dawn Rises Sig Songwriter to Shine at Top of Pop Charts|url=|journal=The Magazine of Sigma Chi|volume=93|issue=2|pages=37|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlex Harvey performed and recorded as a musician throughout the 1970s and 1980s. Harvey's songs have been recorded by many other significant artists such as [[Alan Jackson]], [[Three Dog Night]], [[Billy Ray Cyrus]], [[Jimmy Buffett]], [[Anne Murray]], [[Eydie Gorm\u00e9]], [[Henry Mancini]], [[Peggy Lee]], and [[Sammy Davis Jr.|Sammy Davis Jr]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/alex-harvey-mn0001310766/songs|title=Alex Harvey {{!}} Songs|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref> [[Kenny Rogers]] alone has recorded eighteen Alex Harvey songs.\n\nTwo of Alex Harvey's greatest hits were \"Reuben James,\" recorded by [[Kenny Rogers]], and \"[[Delta Dawn]],\" recorded by [[Tanya Tucker]], [[Helen Reddy]] and [[Bette Midler]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Canfield|first=Jack|date=May 3, 2011|title=Delta Dawn|url=|journal=Chicken Soup for the Soul: Country Music: The Inspirational Stories Behind 101 of Your Favorite Country Songs|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 1973, Alex Harvey's \"Delta Dawn\" was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]], however, the Grammy was awarded to [[Kenny O'Dell]] for writing [[Charlie Rich]]'s \"[[Behind Closed Doors (Charlie Rich song)|Behind Closed Doors]].\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Million Selling Records from the 1900s to the 1980s: An Illustrated Directory|last=Murrells|first=Joseph|publisher=Batsford|year=1984|isbn=9780668064590|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/millionsellingre00murr/page/372 372]|url=https://archive.org/details/millionsellingre00murr/page/372}}</ref>\n\nHe died on April 4, 2020.<ref>[http://www.cmt.com/news/1819901/alex-harvey-writer-of-delta-dawn-and-reuben-james-dies/ Alex Harvey, Writer of \u201cDelta Dawn\u201d and \u201cReuben James,\u201d Dies]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nPer the [[Library of Congress]] [[National Union Catalog]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=National Union Catalog 1973-1977: Music, Books on Music, and Sound Recordings|last=|first=|publisher=Library of Congress|year=1978|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=116}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Harvey|first=Alex|title=No place but Texas|date=1986|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchCode=LCCN&searchArg=95787317&searchType=1&permalink=y|publisher=Tam Records|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* ''Alex Harvey'' (1971) \n* ''Souvenirs'' (1972)\n* ''True Love'' (1973)\n* ''Preshus'' (1976)\n* ''Purple Crush'' (1977)\n* ''No Place But Texas'' (1986)\n* ''Black and Red'' (1995)\n* ''Eden'' (1997)\n* ''Arms of An Angel'' (2001)\n* ''Luminary'' (2002)\n* ''Peace'' (2003)\n* ''The Songwriter'' (2004)\n* ''Galilee'' (2005)\n* ''Texas 101'' (2015)\n* ''Heart of The Art In Song'' (2018)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs artist|434848}}\n* {{IMDb name|367411}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Alex}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American alternative country musicians]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Murray State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Haywood County, Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{About|the American singer/songwriter from Tennessee|the Scottish musician|The Alex Harvey Band}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Alex Harvey\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter, author, actor, radio host\n| birth_name       = Thomas Alexander Harvey\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1941|3|10}}\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2020|4|4|1941|3|10}}\n| genre            = [[Americana (music)|Americana]]\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[United Artists]], [[Buddah Records|Buddah]], [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]]\n| birth_place      = [[Haywood County, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| website          = http://deltadawn.org\n}}\n'''Thomas Alexander Harvey''' (March 10, 1941<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/statesman/obituary.aspx?n=thomas-harvey&pid=195919421&fhid=12001 Thomas Harvey 1941-2020]</ref> \u2013 April 4, 2020) was an American singer, songwriter, author, actor, and radio host.\n\n== History ==\nAlex Harvey was born in rural western Tennessee near [[Brownsville, Tennessee|Brownsville]]. In 1964, Harvey graduated from [[Murray State University]] in Kentucky with a Master's Degree in Music and Education, and he also studied acting in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1974|title=Dawn Rises Sig Songwriter to Shine at Top of Pop Charts|url=|journal=The Magazine of Sigma Chi|volume=93|issue=2|pages=37|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlex Harvey performed and recorded as a musician throughout the 1970s and 1980s. Harvey's songs have been recorded by many other significant artists such as [[Alan Jackson]], [[Three Dog Night]], [[Billy Ray Cyrus]], [[Jimmy Buffett]], [[Anne Murray]], [[Eydie Gorm\u00e9]], [[Henry Mancini]], [[Peggy Lee]], and [[Sammy Davis Jr.|Sammy Davis Jr]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/alex-harvey-mn0001310766/songs|title=Alex Harvey {{!}} Songs|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref> [[Kenny Rogers]] alone has recorded eighteen Alex Harvey songs.\n\nTwo of Alex Harvey's greatest hits were \"Reuben James,\" recorded by [[Kenny Rogers]], and \"[[Delta Dawn]],\" recorded by [[Tanya Tucker]], [[Helen Reddy]] and [[Bette Midler]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Canfield|first=Jack|date=May 3, 2011|title=Delta Dawn|url=|journal=Chicken Soup for the Soul: Country Music: The Inspirational Stories Behind 101 of Your Favorite Country Songs|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 1973, Alex Harvey's \"Delta Dawn\" was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]], however, the Grammy was awarded to [[Kenny O'Dell]] for writing [[Charlie Rich]]'s \"[[Behind Closed Doors (Charlie Rich song)|Behind Closed Doors]].\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Million Selling Records from the 1900s to the 1980s: An Illustrated Directory|last=Murrells|first=Joseph|publisher=Batsford|year=1984|isbn=9780668064590|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/millionsellingre00murr/page/372 372]|url=https://archive.org/details/millionsellingre00murr/page/372}}</ref>\n\nHe died on April 4, 2020.<ref>[http://www.cmt.com/news/1819901/alex-harvey-writer-of-delta-dawn-and-reuben-james-dies/ Alex Harvey, Writer of \u201cDelta Dawn\u201d and \u201cReuben James,\u201d Dies]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nPer the [[Library of Congress]] [[National Union Catalog]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=National Union Catalog 1973-1977: Music, Books on Music, and Sound Recordings|last=|first=|publisher=Library of Congress|year=1978|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=116}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Harvey|first=Alex|title=No place but Texas|date=1986|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchCode=LCCN&searchArg=95787317&searchType=1&permalink=y|publisher=Tam Records|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* ''Alex Harvey'' (1971) \n* ''Souvenirs'' (1972)\n* ''True Love'' (1973)\n* ''Preshus'' (1976)\n* ''Purple Crush'' (1977)\n* ''No Place But Texas'' (1986)\n* ''Black and Red'' (1995)\n* ''Eden'' (1997)\n* ''Arms of An Angel'' (2001)\n* ''Luminary'' (2002)\n* ''Peace'' (2003)\n* ''The Songwriter'' (2004)\n* ''Galilee'' (2005)\n* ''Texas 101'' (2015)\n* ''Heart of The Art In Song'' (2018)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs artist|434848}}\n* {{IMDb name|367411}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Alex}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American alternative country musicians]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Murray State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Haywood County, Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Harvey_(country_musician)"}
{"title_page": "Sonic Wings Special", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox VG\n| title = Sonic Wings Special\n| image = Sonic Wings Special cover.png\n| caption = Sega Saturn cover art\n| developer = [[Video System]]\n| publisher = {{vgrelease|JP|MediaQuest<br />[[Hamster Corporation|HAMSTER Corporation]]|EU|[[Phoenix Games B.V.]]|AUS|[[THQ]]}}\n| director = K. Matsunami<br>Pirowo\n| programmer = KNT.<br>Yukio Kaneda\n| composer = T. Hosokawa<br>Naoki Itamura\n| released = '''Sega Saturn'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 5, 1996}}'''PlayStation'''{{vgrelease|JP|August 30, 1996|EU|August 12, 2004}}'''Arcade'''<br>1997<br>'''PlayStation Network'''{{vgrelease|JP|August 30, 2007|NA|November 16, 2010|PAL|October 5, 2011}}'''Android'''{{vgrelease|WW|March 14, 2012}}\n| platforms = [[Sega Saturn]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[PlayStation Network]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| genre = [[Shoot 'em up]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sonic Wings Special''''' is a 1996 vertical-scrolling [[shoot 'em up]] that combines the features in ''[[Sonic Wings]]'', ''[[Aero Fighters 2|Sonic Wings 2]]'', and ''[[Sonic Wings 3]]''.\n\nIt was ported to arcade as '''''Sonic Wings Limited'''''. It runs on a Sony ZN-1 [[Japan Amusement Machine and Marketing Association|JAMMA]] board.\n\n==Gameplay==\n===Fighters===\nThere are 7 teams, 14 pilots, and 26 fighters in this game, with each team consisting of 2 members, and a choice of 2 fighters per pilot, except the secret team, which has 1 fighter per pilot.\n\nOnce a player has chosen a team, the other player can only choose a pilot and fighter of the respective team.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Team!!Pilot!!Normal fighter!!Secret fighter\n|-\n|rowspan=2|USA||Blaster Keaton/Mecha-Keaton||[[Lockheed F-117 Nighthawk|F117 Sea Hawk]]||[[Vought F4U Corsair|F4-U Corsair]]\n|-\n|Captain Silver||[[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 Thunderbolt II]]||[[Northrop P-61 Black Widow|P-61 Black Widow]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Japan||Hien||[[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|FS-X]]||[[Nakajima J1N|Gekkou]]\n|-\n|Mao Mao||[[McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle|F-15]]||[[Aichi M6A|Seiran]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Russia||Volk||[[Kamov Ka-50|Ka-50 Hokum]]||[[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-3|Mig 3]]\n|-\n|Chaika & Pooshika||[[Ilyushin Il-102|IL-102]]|| [[Ilyushin Il-2|IL-2 Stormovik]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Sweden||Kowful the Viking||[[Saab 37 Viggen|AJ-37 Viggen]]||[[Junkers Ju 87|Ju 87G Stuka]]\n|-\n|T.B. A-10||[[Lockheed F-104 Starfighter|F-104 Star Fighter]]||[[Brewster F2A Buffalo|B-239 Buffalo]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|P.K.F.||Whity||[[Northrop YF-23|YF-23]]||[[Henschel Hs 129|Hs129]]\n|-\n|Lord River N. White||[[McDonnell Douglas AV-8B Harrier II|AV-8 Harrier II Plus]]||[[Boulton Paul Defiant]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|NATO||Anjera||[[Dassault Rafale|Rafale M]]||[[Dewoitine D.520|Dowoitine D520]]\n|-\n|Ellen & Cincia||[[Grumman F-14 Tomcat|F-14 Tomcat]]||[[Fairey Swordfish|Sword Fish]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Secret||Kotomi||Aka-Usagi||-\n|-\n|The Man||[[Lamborghini Diablo]] (Diabloon) ||-\n|}\n\nA pilot's secret fighter is unlocked by completing the game with the chosen pilot.\n\nThe NATO and Secret teams are unlocked by unlocking all secret fighters in the US, Japan, Russia, Sweden, and P.K.F. teams.\n\n===Stages===\nThere are 17 stages in this game, but only 9 are playable at a time. After completing stage 1, 3 stages are randomly chosen out of 5. The game includes a branching system that allows players to choose 1 of 2 branches after completing stages 5, 7, or 8.\n\nIf a secret fighter is chosen, alternate versions of the stages appear instead.\n\n==PlayStation version==\nIt allows saving the game for more than once per round,{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} while the PAL version doesn't support the [[Memory card#Video game consoles|PS1 Memorycard]] at all.\n\n==Arcade version==\nThere are 6 teams, 12 pilots, and 12 fighters in this version. There are 10 stages but only 7 are playable per game. After completing Stage 4, Stage 5 and 6 are chosen depending on the player's performance. After completing Stage 6, one of Fight in Orbit, Another Dimension, or Mars becomes Stage 7, depending on the player's performance. In Fight in Orbit, Another Dimension, 1 of 2 different final bosses appear in the end. If all lives are lost in Stage 7, continuing causes the game to start at the beginning of a stage. If one of the five last stage bosses is not defeated before it escapes, a boss-specific failure ending is shown. A character-specific ending is shown if the final Stage 7 boss is defeated, and a stage-specific ending is shown. After an item is revealed, the point value of the item increases the longer it stays on screen. The point value progresses at the sequence of 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000, 4000, and 10000 (maximum) points.\n\n==Reception==\n{{video game reviews\n|rev1 = ''Super GamePower''\n|rev1Score = 3.5<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Bros|first=Marjorie|date=July 1998|title=Saturn: Sonic Wings Special|url=|magazine=Super GamePower|language=PT|location=Brazil|publisher=Nova Cultural|issue=31|page=19|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hamster.co.jp/american_hamster/products/soft.cgi?ps3&e87137 HAMSTER page]\n*[https://archive.is/20040722110226/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/release1a.htm Phoenix Games page]\n*[http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~bevhome/swscans.htm DAM: Sonic Wings Special - Sega Saturn]\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/game/sonic-wings-special ''Sonic Wings Special''] at [[MobyGames]]\n*[https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9630 ''Sonic Wings Limited''] at the [[Killer List of Videogames]]\n\n{{Aero Fighters series}}\n\n[[Category:1996 video games]]\n[[Category:2004 video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Sega Saturn games]]\n[[Category:Vertically scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Soshi Hosoi]]\n[[Category:THQ games]]\n[[Category:Video System games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox VG\n|title = Sonic Wings Special\n|image = Sonic Wings Special cover.png\n|caption = Sega Saturn cover art\n|developer = [[Video System]]\n|publisher = {{vgrelease|JP|MediaQuest<br />[[Hamster Corporation|HAMSTER Corporation]]|EU|[[Phoenix Games B.V]]|AUS|[[THQ]]}}\n|director = K. Matsunami<br>Pirowo\n|programmer = KNT.<br>Yukio Kaneda\n|composer = T. Hosokawa<br>Naoki Itamura\n|released = '''Sega Saturn'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 5, 1996}}'''PlayStation'''{{vgrelease|JP|August 30, 1996|EU|August 12, 2004}}'''Arcade'''<br>1997<br>'''PlayStation Network'''{{vgrelease|JP|August 30, 2007|NA|November 16, 2010|PAL|October 5, 2011}}'''Android'''{{vgrelease|WW|March 14, 2012}}\n|platforms = [[Sega Saturn]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[PlayStation Network]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n|genre = [[Shoot 'em up]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sonic Wings Special''''' is a 1996 vertical-scrolling [[shoot 'em up]] that combines the features in ''[[Sonic Wings]]'', ''[[Aero Fighters 2|Sonic Wings 2]]'', and ''[[Sonic Wings 3]]''.\n\nIt was ported to arcade as '''''Sonic Wings Limited'''''. It runs on a Sony ZN-1 [[Japan Amusement Machine and Marketing Association|JAMMA]] board.\n\n==Gameplay==\n===Fighters===\nThere are 7 teams, 14 pilots, and 26 fighters in this game, with each team consisting of 2 members, and a choice of 2 fighters per pilot, except the secret team, which has 1 fighter per pilot.\n\nOnce a player has chosen a team, the other player can only choose a pilot and fighter of the respective team.\n\n{| class=